      "content": "It is true that general economic growth has significantly improved living standards for many Americans over the last century. However, historical data also shows that specific legislative victories, like minimum wage laws and workplace safety standards, were often achieved through organized labor pressure, not just organic market forces. Unions have historically played a crucial role in pushing for these specific protections that move beyond simple wage increases. Therefore, while growth is vital, unions have been a distinct catalyst for structural worker rights.",
